    "title": "The Weaver of Shadows",
    "story": "
      In the high cliffs of **Veythar’s Spire**, there lived a weaver named **Sylria**, whose tapestries shimmered with impossible colors—threads spun from moonlight, dyed in starlight, and woven with whispers of the future. The villagers below revered her, trading grain and wool for glimpses of fate. But Sylria’s art was a lie. She stole the threads from the **Fates’ Loom**, a sacred device hidden in the **Cave of Unseen Hands**, and her tapestries were merely echoes of stolen time.

      One winter, Sylria tricked the village elder, **Orlan**, into giving her his last sheep in exchange for a tapestry that ‘would show his son’s safe return from war.’ Orlan, grief-stricken, agreed. But when the tapestry unraveled at dawn, it revealed only **empty threads**—his son had perished, and Sylria had known. The villagers, realizing her deception, stormed the spire, but Sylria fled, leaving behind a single, half-finished tapestry: a warning of her own undoing.

      The **Fates**, enraged, sent their **Hands**—pale, long-fingered spirits—to hunt her. They caught Sylria in the **Forest of Echoes**, where every lie she had ever woven played back as a scream. As punishment, the Fates forced her to **weave her own fate**: a tapestry that would strangle her if she ever spoke another falsehood. Sylria, desperate, wove a single truth—*‘I am the thief of time, and time will have its due.’*—and the tapestry tightened around her throat.

      But the cycle ended when Orlan, still mourning, found Sylria’s abandoned loom. He burned it, declaring, *‘No more stolen futures.’* The Fates, satisfied, withdrew their Hands, and the villagers learned to **weave their own tapestries of memory**, no longer trusting outsiders’ promises of fate.
    "
  }
}
```

